conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Thomas de Calthorpe was born in 1169, in Little Hautbois, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of William Calthorpe."},"et":{"1169–":"1169–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1171–1239":"1171–1239","–Female":"Surnud","1194–1257":"1194–1257","1222–1257":"1222–1257","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1230–1260":"1230–1260","1126–1169":"1126–1169","1228":"1228","1239":"1239","1126":"1126","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1222":"1222","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","1171":"1171","Little Hautbois, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Little Hautbois, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1169–":"1169–Kuollut","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1171–1239":"1171–1239","–Female":"Kuollut","1194–1257":"1194–1257","1222–1257":"1222–1257","1224–Female":"1224–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1230–1260":"1230–1260","1126–1169":"1126–1169","1228":"1228","1239":"1239","1126":"1126","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1257